      "content": "At the connection point, the top of the cantilevered balcony beam is under tension, while the bottom is under compression. This is because the beam is being pulled on at the top (the wall connection) and pushed on at the bottom (the ground or floor connection).\n\nImagine the beam as a giant's arm, with the wall at the shoulder and the ground at the elbow. The wall tries to pull the arm upwards, creating tension at the top. The ground pushes down on the elbow, creating compression at the bottom. This tension and compression are what allow the beam to resist bending and maintain its shape, much like a giant's arm can hold a heavy object without bending.\n\nThe stress distribution along the beam is not uniform. It varies from the top to the bottom, with the maximum tension occurring at the top near the wall connection and the maximum compression at the bottom near the ground connection. The stress distribution is typically linear, with the highest stresses at the ends of the beam and zero at the midpoint, assuming the beam is simply supported at the ends and has no overhang. This linear distribution of stress is a result of the bending moment, which is highest at the ends and decreases towards the middle of the beam.",
